SIMPLE: usurpation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Usurpation
<hw>U`sur*pa"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>usurpatio <?/</ets> making use, usurpation: cf. F.
<ets>usurpation</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of usurping, or of seizing and enjoying; an
authorized, arbitrary assumption and exercise of power, especially an
infringing on the rights of others; specifically, the illegal seizure of
sovereign power; -- commonly used with <xex>of</xex>, also used with
<xex>on</xex> or <xex>upon</xex>; <as>as, the <ex>usurpation</ex> of a
throne; the <ex>usurpation</ex> of the supreme power</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1589 -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He contrived their destruction, with the <qex>usurpation</qex> of
the regal dignity upon him.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. More.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A law [of a State] which is a <qex>usurpation</qex> upon the
general government.</q> <rj><qau>O. Ellsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Manifest <qex>usurpation</qex> on the rights of other States.</q>
<rj><qau>D. Webster.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Usurpation</xex>, in a peculiar sense, formerly
denoted the absolute ouster and dispossession of the patron of a church,
by a stranger presenting a clerk to a vacant benefice, who us thereupon
admitted and instituted.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Use; usage; custom.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bp. Pearson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Usurpatory</ent>⟦br⟧
